<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-845-686  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 845 686.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  Sept 12 1990 n1510* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Ingres comes out with Windows 4GL, WindowView to facilitateapplications development. (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ingres Corp. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    RELY.andO;Product:   Windows 4GL (Program development software) (product introduction)WindowView (Program development software) (product introduction)Microsoft Windows 3.0 (Graphical user interface) (equipment andsupplies).andO;Topic:     Program Development ToolsApplications ProgrammingUser Interface Management SystemsFourth-Generation LanguagesWindowing.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>INGRES COMES OUT WITH WINDOWS 4GL, WINDOWVIEW TOandM;FACILITATE APPLICATIONS DEVELOPMENTandM;Ingres Corp has released a windows-based development tool for relationaldatabase management systems, which it claims is the first to make full use ofthe graphical capabilities offered by windows.andP;  Windows 4GL is based on theterminal version of Ingres' applications generator, although the windowsversion has taken 20 extra man-years to develop.andP;  Like Oracle, Informix andothers, Ingres already has a &quot;fourth generation language&quot; databasedevelopment tool which uses windows - the Ingres version is calledWindowView.andP;  But Ingres says its new product is superior to other windowsprograms because it was specifically written for windows with the enhancedgraphical capabilities of a workstation in mind, rather than essentiallybeing a terminal system which can be run on a workstation.andP;  Initially, thesoftware will run on workstations only - Sun Sparcstations and DEC VAXesunder VMS - but next year it will be available for personal computers underMicrosoft's Windows 3.0.andP;  This is because the workstation market for databasedevelopment systems is tiny compared with that of personal computers andterminals.andP;  Despite emphasising the true workstation capabilities of theproduct, Ingres says it will not lose any functionality when it is run on apersonal computer.andP;  Product manager Mark Hanner says personal computers andworkstations, which he terms &quot;microstations&quot; now have almost the samecapabilities - especially when Windows 3.0 is running on the personalcomputer.andP;  As for WindowView, the Ingres terminal-based tool, Hanner reckonsthat this will not become redundant.andP;  Ingres will continue to market it &quot;forpeople who already have terminals installed and won't want to take up thenewer technology immediately&quot;.andP;  It is an &quot;evolutionary solution&quot;.andP;  UsingWindows 4GL, programmers can access any native windows environment so thatdevelopers can use facilities from any native window programs they have ontheir machines.andP;  This also means that an application built in DECwindows, forexample, can be run under any window system with no code changes.andP;  Featuresthat users get with Windows 4GL compared with a product like WindowViewinclude the use of radio buttons, applications running simultaneously inmultiple windows and bit-mapped images.andP;  Ingres also claims a 10-foldincrease in productivity over a using a conventional high level languagedevelopment environment, achieved through a reduction in the amount of codethat the programmer needs to write.andP;  By the end of the year the software willbe available to run under Ultrix as well as VMS, and on the Hewlett-PackardHP9000 under HP-UX, and the IBM RS/6000 under AIX Unix.andP;  The cost is around#1,000 per user.andO;</TEXT></DOC>